    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-08-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-08-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="884"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d884">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.6131/623</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Soviet Embassy</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Aide-Mémoire</hi>
                    <note n="97" xml:id="d884fn97">An attached notation dated July 30, 1941, by Loy
                        W. Henderson, Assistant Chief of the Division of European Affairs, reads as
                        follows: “During the course of the Soviet Ambassador’s call this afternoon
                        he was handed a copy of the attached <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi>,
                        with the understanding that it will be initialed when the notes are signed.
                        The Ambassador was informed that although the <hi rend="italic"
                            >aide-mémoire</hi> will not be published, it will not be regarded as
                        confidential in character.”</note>
                </p>
                <p>With respect to the exchange of notes continuing in force the 1937 commercial
                    agreement with the Soviet Union, without the accompanying <pb facs="0937"
                        n="925" xml:id="pg_925"/> related notes exchanged in 1940, it should be
                    noted that if at any time during the agreement year it should appear that
                    imports of Soviet coal into the United States would exceed the figure of 400,000
                    tons mentioned in the Soviet note of August 6, 1940 limiting exports of coal to
                    the United States, the Government of the United States would feel free to
                    consult with the Soviet Government with a view to arriving at a satisfactory
                    adjustment of the matter.</p>
                <closer>
                    <dateline rendition="#left">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-08-02">August 2,
                            1941</date>.</dateline>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
